[{"review_id":"Ci9DQUlRQUNvZENodHljRjlvT2pOTVlVMU9Nbmd0YTB4TlRscDRlbTFFVVV4YVRsRRAB","review_link":"https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sCi9DQUlRQUNvZENodHljRjlvT2pOTVlVMU9Nbmd0YTB4TlRscDRlbTFFVVV4YVRsRRAB!2m1!1s0x0:0x81fe86cbbfbd89a4!3m1!1s2@1:CAIQACodChtycF9oOjNMYU1OMngta0xNTlp4em1EUUxaTlE%7C0d0WhHuMkT7%7C?hl=en-GB","name":"The Travel Hunter","reviewer_id":"108039684423738859787","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/108039684423738859787?hl=en-GB","rating":5,"review_text":"
The Friday Night Market in George Town is a fantastic experience full of life, colors, and delicious aromas! It perfectly captures the local Penang vibe -- friendly vendors, great street food, handmade crafts, and live music that creates a fun, festive atmosphere. The variety of snacks and local specialties is amazing, from satay to desserts and refreshing drinks. Prices are reasonable, and the crowd adds to the excitement rather than chaos. Lots of food stalls and there are kids wear, socks, sandals and mobile phone accessories along at pedestrian lot left and right side.
I try the egg waffle (6myr for 5pcs), fried stall (myr14.5 for around 6pcs radish cake, 6pcs dumpling, 2 otak-otak), steam dimsum (12myr for 10pcs), Yong tau fu in car (myr6 for 8pcs), pork satay for myr3.5/pcs.
Best one is steam dimsum, I quite confident saying it because even the seller eat the dimsum, I mean rarely to find someone who eat their own stuff but yet he is, either it is because he made it by himself or it is unpredictable delicious. Buy the one with plain colour more, because it taste more original.
2nd best is Yong tau fu, the chili and sauce is great.
Pork satay nice but have fishy taste (amis) there are 3 stall totally selling this pork satay the looks is same..
For fried stall quite interested in the beginning because the seller keep giving everyone 1pc free to try but when selling, they sell to me 3 kind of stuff and I must pay myr14.5 and eat till bored, so this fried stuff is nice if you eat it with more friends.
Egg waffle is nice too, but I think is just ordinary.
There is also socks stall that selling socks use bamboo so will not have bad odor after long usage, I don't buy it but the material is thick, maybe worth to try as other review saying Ling","reviewer_id":"115707001285123682601","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/115707001285123682601?hl=en-GB","rating":4,"review_text":"Heard that this night market only opens on a Friday by the locals, and I'm so glad we managed to visit this place while we are here!

It's a super long stretch (about 1km) of street vendors in tiny food trucks and tentage mainly selling traditional penang food and some street food typically found in Asian night markets.

On the opposite side sells slightly similar things, but mainly non-food items like clothes and phone equipment.

I would say this leans towards more of a local audience than tourists (compared to George Town), but variety is quite repetitive. For instance, there are 2 of the same brands selling sugar cane juice on the same stretch, and also Char Kueih Kak.

Prices wise, for each main, it is about 8RM onwards, but it's a pretty non-tourist place to get a quick fix of the local night market scene.

Though this place closes at 10pm, the stores start to pack up when they are done for the day around 9:15 pm onwards. Chua","reviewer_id":"115818807181592198440","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/115818807181592198440?hl=en-GB","rating":4,"review_text":"Nice and simple night market with plenty of food choices & some goods to buy!
I think this night market is mostly for the locals as they featured food and daily necessities. Not really for tourists as they didn't have any souvenirs for purchase.
However, it was fun for us to see and try the food. Most of it was really yummy, but a lot of it was really unhealthy.
If you're a tourist and happen to be in Penang on a Wednesday, do try to make your way down and have some good local food! I at muah Chee, fried chicken drumstick, keropok lekor, dessert, durians, fried man tou, fried squid and had a super fresh freshly squeezed soursop juice. The juice was sour and yummy! Loved that.
If you're a local, for the sake of your health, pls don't come here more than once a month! Haha...

Open on select nights, this local night market offers a vibrant atmosphere with a wide range of street food options, from local favorites like char koay teow, apam balik, lok lok, and satay, to refreshing drinks and sweet treats.

Prices range from cheap to reasonable, making it perfect for budget-conscious foodies or tourists wanting to sample multiple dishes without breaking the bank.

It's also a great place to soak in the local culture, mingle with friendly vendors, and enjoy the bustling night scene. Whether you're a local or a visitor, this night market is a great one-stop spot to experience the flavors of Penang.

Tip: Go early to avoid the crowd and to get the freshest picks! idrus","reviewer_id":"110656667041441614120","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/110656667041441614120?hl=en-GB","rating":4,"review_text":"One of the more convenient places to park and can serve as a focal point if you want to have a good walk exploring the area.

There is a wet market on the bottom floor and you can get raw ingredient as well as the variety of assam/jeruk products here.

I usually go here for the cucur udang next door and the secondhand bookstores within the building. Some of the mamaks are really good at sourcing books and will give you good prices. They usually have old books but sometimes if you're lucky they have a pretty good selection of new ones. Not bad options if you only have budget to pay less than the retail price.

I also had a good experience at one of the stores selling souvenirs that opened early morning even though the rest of the shops weren't open yet. We ended up buying a lot because the staff made us feel like VVIP with their good customer service. I don't know the name of the store but it's right next to the escalator with the hanging kaftans on the second floor. The local chinese gentleman was very fluent in Malay and was very friendly and attentive. He was happily promoting the goods without forcing us so shopping here was a pleasant experience. Recommended!","published_at":"6 months Martin 1818","reviewer_id":"116675375590051310522","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/116675375590051310522?hl=en-GB","rating":null,"review_text":"@ Gurney Drive Hawker Centre (Xin Guan Zi Jiao Xiao Fan Zhong Xin)
@ 172, Solok Gurney 1, Pulau Tikus, 10250 Jelutong, Pulau Pinang.

Came on Monday to avoid the weekend crowd but only 30% of the Chinese stalls were open. The Muslin food stalls were all opened.
Reach the placec at about 5pm & not many customers were there yet. It was  about an hour later around 6pm, the place started to get more people and became crowded...  This hawker centre is famous  among the tourists and has attracted may tourists from all over different places.  Nevertheless, this spot is definitely not the best place that provide the Penang best local delicacies & foodies.
Have tried a few of the foodie and in general, most of the food were just average.
For preference, the Assam Laksa was a slightly better dish to have. RM7 for big portion bowl & RM6  for small portion bowl. The paper bowl were all the same size but the portion of noodle was slightly more for the big portion. The soup base tastes was good...4stars...

The two char koay teow stalls were not  with long queue but both stalls their  price has gone quite high ...
One of the stall is selling RM 11(with chicken egg) & RM 12(with duck egg).
The other stall is selling RM 10(with chicken egg) & RM 11(with duck egg).
Reckon that they were not quite worth giving a try... 2stars","published_at":"a year The street is lined with hawker stalls selling some of the island's favourite local dishes.

5 stars for the street side atmosphere. Seemingly chaotic with tourists, both local and foreign, staggering on the road trying to place their orders or figure what's on the menu of each stalls.

It is not a clean environment - it is street side after all but that is a part of the experience. You can sit at any tables lined on curbside or on the five foot walkway. It is literally sitting next to a drain, or on top of it. It only opens at night which was a good thing otherwise you might can roaches  or rodent scrurrying by the drains.

Food-wise, I have tried the wantan noodle (pretty good), white curry noodle (average, forgettable) and apom (way too thin).

The wantan noodle had a nice springiness to bite. Its sauce savoury and strong. Char siew deceptively flavourful. Fried wantan dumpling a miss.

Would I come back for the food? As a local foodie, nope. Would I recommend travelers to pass by? Yes. The street around the corner itself is lined with pretty good restaurants and cafes - so you have a choice of eating well before soaking up the chaotic charm of street side hawker I would recommend several things which I found worth trying:

- Duck egg char koay teow sold by an old uncle (see photo). This is one of the best ckt I've eaten. Must give it a shot.

name: Plaza Ramadan Prangin Mall
description:
Kerajaan Negeri Pulau Pinang, Prangin Mall dan Penang Halal International bersama menganjurkan program Plaza Ramadan. Di sini terdapat banyak gerai yang menjual pelbagai jenis juadah berbuka puasa termasuk nasi biryani, kuih-muih tradisional dan moden serta pelbagai aneka minuman yang menyegarkan, pakaian dan barang serbaneka.

Masa: 3 petang - 9 malam

The noodles were perfectly fried with a nice springy texture, and the prawns were fresh and juicy.

Portion size is generous for the price, and the waiting time was quite reasonable even during busy hours. You can really taste the skill and consistency in each plate -- simple, local, and done right.

Batu Lanchang Public Market:
This market is a very famous public market in the Batu Lanchang area. It provides various types of daily necessities such as vegetables, fruit, fish, meat and fresh food. This public market is often a meeting place for local residents to buy daily goods.
This market is also known for its activity in the morning and is a destination for those looking for fresh goods at reasonable prices.
Batu Lanchang People's Hall:
The people's hall is a community center that is often used for various community activities, such as meetings, cultural events, community classes, and also as a place for volunteer activities.

Jia Sheng","reviewer_id":"118317192168151606174","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/118317192168151606174?hl=en-GB","rating":4,"review_text":"A local market with many food and daily necessities options, you tiao was surprisingly good.

Notes for tourist:
You can buy food from any stall and sit anywhere but for most market/coffeeshop in Penang, you are expected to buy a drink from them.
Different drink stalls have their allocated area to sell their drinks and that's why shortly after you take a seat, someone will approach you for drinks.
